5 Intro to ggplot2

Visualising data is an efficient way to understand our data and communicate our work. There are several packages in R for producing statistical, or data, graphics. This week we focus on inspecting/visualising our data and check assumptions using several functions from base R or a very cool package ggplot2.

ggplot is based on Grammar of Graphics. ggplot is very powerful in a way that we can build and customise our graphics. We can do this by building layer by layer by adding geom elements. This workshop only covers the basics of ggplot2. Lets start with ggplot2 formula.

The base formula to build ggplot is ggplot(data, mapping) + geoms().

  • ggplot() builds base plot.
  • data binds the plot to a specific dataset.
  • mapping uses the aesthetic aes() function to select variables to be plotted and specify how to present them in the graph, e.g., as x/y positions or characteristics such as size, shape, color, etc.
  • geoms() adds geoms to specify how to represent the data in the plot (points, lines, bars).

Common geoms, some of which we will be using today:

  • geom_point() scatter plots, dot plots, etc.
  • geom_line() trend lines, etc.
  • geom_boxplot() boxplots.
  • geom_smooth() to check patterns in your data (e.g., linearity).
  • geom_histogram() and geom_density() to check distribution.
# example scatter plot
ggplot(d,
       aes(
         x = Variable1,
         y = Variable2)) + 
  geom_point()

# example line plot
ggplot(d[1:10, ],
       aes(
         x = Variable1,
         y = Variable2)) + 
  geom_line()

6 Assumptions

We often use graphs to visually assess assumptions, such as normality and for outliers. There are several ways to check assumptions in R. You can choose from Base R or ggplot2. Its up to you which functions you use, they will probably ultimately give you the same results. Lets apply ggplot principles to inspect our data and check assumptions.

6.1 Linearity

6.1.1 Scatter Plot

Scatter Plot is probably the easiest way to check linearity.

Code Template for Scatter Plot

  • For Base R, use plot() function: plot(dataset_name$iv_name, dataset_name$dv_name)
  • For ggplot, use geom_point() function
# base R plot
plot(d$Variable1, d$Variable2)
# ggplot
ggplot(d,
       aes(
         x = Variable1,
         y = Variable2)) +  
  geom_point()

6.1.2 Adding a line to Scatter Plot

We can add a line to the plot to visualise the data/relationship easily by using the geom_smooth() function.

ggplot(d,
       aes(
         x = Variable1,
         y = Variable2)) +  
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = 'lm', se = FALSE)
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

You Try It

Check Linearity assumption using 2 variables that you just scored. Does their relationship follow a straight line?

6.2 Normality

6.2.1 Shapiro-Wilk test

Code Template for Shapiro-Wilk test

shapiro.test(dataset_name$variable_name)

shapiro.test(d$Variable1)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  d$Variable1
## W = 1, p-value = 0.5

6.2.2 Histogram

Code Template for Histogram

  • For Base R, use hist() function: hist(dataset_name$variable_name)
  • For ggplot, use geom_histogram() or geom_density()


# base R
hist(d$Variable1)
# ggplot
ggplot(d,
       aes(x = Variable1)) + 
  geom_histogram()
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

We can also use a density plot using the geom_density() function, which also attempts to show the distribution, but using a smooth density function rather than binning the data and plotting the frequencies like how the geom_histogram() does.

ggplot(d,
       aes(x = Variable1)) + 
  geom_density()

6.2.3 QQ Plot

Code Template for QQ Plot

qplot(sample = variable_name, data = dataset_name)

qplot(sample = Variable1, data = d)

6.2.4 Box plots

Boxplots can be used to visualize the distribution of variables and extreme values.

# ggplot
ggplot(d,
       aes(
         x = Variable1)) +  
  geom_boxplot(color = "#7F7F7F", fill = "#FAF7F3")

6.2.5 Box plot by groups

We can also use boxplot to check distribution of variables in different groups. Here I compare the distribution of Variable 1 between males and females.

ggplot(d,
       aes(
         x = as.factor(Sex),
         y = Variable1)) + 
  geom_boxplot(color = "#7F7F7F", fill = "#FAF7F3")

6.3 Normality of Residuals

Normality of Residuals is checked using our linear regression model, which means we need a model first. We will be learning about fitting linear regression in R later, but lets quickly run a model to check Normality of residuals. Lets call our model object m.

Code Template for Linear Regression Model

lm(dv_name ~ iv_name, data = dataset_name)

m <- lm(Variable1 ~ Age, data = d)

Code Template for checking Normality of Residuals

plot(model_name, 2)

plot(m, 2)

You Try It

Run a linear regression model and check Normality of Residuals assumption. Is the assumption met?

6.4 Homogeneity of Variance

6.4.1 Homoscedasticity

Similar to Normality of Residuals, we also need our model to check Homoscedasticity.

Code Template for checking Homoscedasticity

plot(model_name, 1)

plot(m, 1)

Code Template for Levenes Test

leveneTest(dv_name ~ iv_name, data = dataset_name)

7 Dealing with Normality and Outliers

Common methods to deal with extreme values are:

  • Removal of extreme values
  • Winsorisation
  • Transformation

Tips

Always inspect your plots again after transformation to check if the transformation has improved/addressed normality/outliers.

7.1 Checking distributions and outliers

Lets use a very useful function testDistribution() combined with plot() from the JWileymisc package to check the distribution of a variable.

There are two parts to this graph that you may find helpful.

  • The distribution of the raw data/variable is represented as a solid black line. A dashed blue line shows what a normal distribution would look like. If these two lines are close, that indicates the variable is approximately normally distributed.
  • Outliers (if any) are identified in black while the rest of data points are light grey. We use extremevalues = "theoretical" argument to identify outliers. We then use ev.perc argument to specify the percentage of the theoretical distribution in each tail we consider extreme. For example ev.perc = .005 means that we consider any score that is in the bottom 0.5% or top 0.5% of a normal distribution to be an extreme value. We can also use the top and bottom 0.1% (ev.perc = .001).
plot(testDistribution(d$Variable1,
                      extremevalues = "theoretical", ev.perc = .005))

7.2 Removal of outliers

7.2.1 Subsetting by IDs

You can remove extreme values/participants by subsetting data by rows (we learnt this in week 3 workshop). As a refresher, when we subset data by rows, we specify our argument(s) in the i section of DT[...]. If our dataset has a ID variable (most dataset does), we can remove them using the participant ID. For example, assuming ID 10 is an outlier, we can remove them using != which means not equal.

d1 <- d[RandomID != 10]

7.2.2 Subsetting using z-scores

Finally, if we assume a variable follows a normal distribution, we may use z scores to identify extreme values or outliers using \(z \pm 3.29\).

We will need to first create z-score for that variable using the scale() function.

d[, ScaledVariable1 := scale(Variable1)]

Check the data using table() function. You can see that there is one extreme value based on z score.

table(d$ScaledVariable1 > 3.29)
## 
## FALSE 
##   380
table(d$ScaledVariable1 < -3.29)
## 
## FALSE  TRUE 
##   379     1

We can remove it using the code below:

d <- d[ScaledVariable1 <3.29 & ScaledVariable1 > -3.29]

7.3 Winsorising

Instead of simply removing the data, we can winsorise them. That means we replace the extreme values with a certain percentile value from each end. We can winsorse our variables using the winsor() function. Use the trim argument to specify how much you would like to winsorise top & bottom (e.g, 0.5% or 1%).

d[, Winsored_Variable1 := winsor(Variable1, trim = .005)]
d[, Winsored_Variable1 := winsor(Variable1, trim = .01)]

7.4 Transformation

There are two common transformations:

  • Log
  • Square root

We can perform these transformations using log() and sqrt().

d[, Log_Variable1 := log(Variable1)]
d[, Sqrt_Variable1 := sqrt(Variable1)]
